<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: TV &amp; VIDEO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALEENE MacMINN, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Stars Head for Hemingway's 'Hills': HBO has lined up a pair of Academy Award 
nominees -- James Woods and Melanie Griffith -- to star in Ernest Hemingway's 
"Hills Like White Elephants." The Hemingway story, about an American expatriate 
couple facing the end of their long affair, is the first film in an HBO 
trilogy, "Men and Women." Joan Didion and John Gregory Dunne will adapt the 
story and Tony Richardson will direct the David Brown production. The trilogy, 
which also includes stories by Dorothy Parker ("Dusk Before Fireworks") and 
Mary McCarthy ("The Man in the Brooks Brothers Shirt") will premiere on HBO 
next summer. ALEENE MacMINN 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Woods 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
