<HEADLINE>
<P>
KHOMEINI SON GETS POSITION ON IRAN'S TOP SECURITY BODY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NICOSIA, Cyprus 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ahmed Khomeini, an outspoken radical and son of Iran's late supreme leader, the 
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, was appointed Monday to the country's top defense 
and security policy-making body. 
</P>
<P>
Tehran Radio said Iran's spiritual leader, the Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, named 
Khomeini, 42, as one of his two personal representatives on the National 
Security Council. 
</P>
<P>
It is the first official post for Khomeini, a clergyman who built a reputation 
as his father's chief aide and personal secretary from the 1979 Islamic 
revolution to the elder Khomeini's death last June. 
</P>
<P>
Ahmed is looked upon by anti-Western radicals as a rallying symbol in the 
post-Khomeini era, being dominated by the more pragmatic President Hashemi 
Rafsanjani. 
</P>
</TEXT>
